Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Pakistan. The Pakistani authorities have introduced a number of measures to limit the spread of the virus.
Entry and travel restrictions
Pakistani authorities have introduced a number of measures to limit the spread of the virus including closures of the border with Iran, Afghanistan and the Wagah border with India.
On 21 March, the government of Pakistan announced the suspension of all international flights to Pakistan, effective from 2000 PST on 21 March until 2000 PST on 4 April. The government of Pakistan described the measure as a ‘temporary suspension imposed due to exceptional circumstances’. We understand that the suspension applies also to international flights out of Pakistan.
Despite this suspension, we understand that Pakistan International Airlines (PIA) may operate flights from Islamabad to UK operating on 27 and 28 March. We understand that PIA flights will only be advertised through travel agents. We understand Qatar Airways is also planning on operating a daily flight from Islamabad International Airport from 25 March until 3 April. For Qatar Airways flights please see website or contact travel agents.
If transiting a third country, please check that you will be able to fly on to the UK. For information on how to return to the UK from Pakistan, see Return to the UK
On 25 March, the government of Pakistan announced the suspension of all domestic flight operations with effect from 0600 PST 26 March until 2 April. Cargo and special flights are exempted from this restrictions. Some internal flights had already been cancelled.
Reinforcement of screening and administrative measures at all sea ports have been announced.
Social measures
Pakistani authorities have introduced a number of measures to limit the spread of the virus including school closures, and banning public gatherings. Some provincial authorities are introducing additional measures, including requiring residents to stay at home, and closing shops and restaurants. Measures are particularly stringent in Sindh and Punjab.On 25 March, Islamabad Capital Territory announced additional measures, including a ban on public transport, except taxis and the ICT Metro Bus, and a ban on public and private social and religious gatherings. As British Nationals should follow the federal and relevant provincial guidance, and monitor local media for updates. Movements should be planned accordingly.
If you are running out of medication or have medical needs, you should speak to your travel insurance company for advice and seek local medical assistance, including from pharmacies. Your GP / UK doctor may be able to advise of alternative medication if yours is not available in Pakistan.
Further information
The Pakistani authorities have announced a helpline on phone number 1166 for people who have recently travelled to China, Iran or a country where COVID-19 is present and who have symptoms like fever, cough and difficulty breathing. British nationals who are worried about the virus, or suspect they may have contracted it, should contact that number and follow the guidance given by the authorities.
Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
You can find more information about cases in Pakistan on the TravelHealthPro website.
